SIMPLE: sorry
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sorry
<hw>Sor"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Sorrier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Sorriest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sory</ets>,
<ets>sary</ets>, AS. <ets>s⟦amac⟧rig</ets>, fr. <ets>s⟦amac⟧r</ets>,
<pos>n.</pos>, <ets>sore</ets>. <ets>See</ets> <er>Sore</er>,
<pos>n.</pos> & <pos>a.</pos> The original sense was, painful; hence,
miserable, sad.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Grieved for the loss of some
good; pained for some evil; feeling regret; -- now generally used to
express light grief or affliction, but formerly often used to express
deeper feeling.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧I am <xex>sorry</xex> for my sins.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye were made <qex>sorry</qex> after a godly manner.</q> <rj><qau>2
Cor. vii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am <qex>sorry</qex> for thee, friend; 't is the duke's
pleasure.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She entered, were he lief or <qex>sorry</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Melancholy; dismal; gloomy; mournful.</def>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All full of chirking was this <qex>sorry</qex> place.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Poor; mean; worthless; <as>as, a <ex>sorry</ex>
excuse</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧With <xex>sorry</xex> grace.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cheeks of <qex>sorry</qex> grain will serve.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Good fruit will sometimes grow on a <qex>sorry</qex> tree.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Hurt; afflicted; mortified; vexed; chagrined;
melancholy; dismal; poor; mean; pitiful.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sors</ent>⟦br⟧
